vity, time/cost/quality constraints, abstraction or hierarchical breakdown. Even these elements may be complex and interdependent so a meticulous approach is needed. Â Further, the know/unknown analysis often quoted to Donald Rumsfeld, ex-US Secretary of Defense, can be invaluable: we might know what we know and what we don\'t know, but how do we find out what we don\'t know we don\'t even know? Often the answer is find someone who has experienced something like this problem before. Â Again its about being very methodical. Â Above all this clue is all about understanding the problem, characterising it, finding out what needs to be better understood andÂ definingÂ it carefully. Â Solving the wrong problem is too often a problem!</li>\r\n 	<li><b>Collect Good Data:</b> From good data, insight and information can be drawn. Â This adds to our knowledge ultimately contributing to wisdom on a subject. This is the basis of good science - but in projects and business good facts are often abstract and scarce, but undeniably still crucial. For example onÂ endeavorsÂ that are significantly off track, often the hardest question to answer is \"where are we?\". Â Digital developments and large organisation changes can often appear to be more progressed than they actually are. Â What is needed are some hard facts: Â What specifically has been achieved? How much in each area actually has been spent? What value are customers receiving? Â How many people are actually booking time? Systematically collecting data is key but there are some health warnings: \"You can\'t control what you can\'t measure\" is an Engineering maxim that applies equally in business. Â However, this needs to be balanced by the flip side that \"what you measure is affected\". How often have you observed unbalanced goals drive the wrong behaviours? (eg sales measured just on revenue diminishes profit).Â  It takes time to gather good facts, especially where the source is not naturally enumerated, but the effort will save time in the long run.</li>\r\n 	<li><b>Analyse &amp; Suspend JudgementÂ </b> Â Once some of the facts start to appear, especially in pressured situations, there is a strong desire to jump to conclusions. This clue is a reminder that cool heads are needed to carefully assess that allÂ dimensionsÂ have been considered and sound data collected. Â Inevitably there will be gaps and for each gap an appropriate assumption will need to be made. Good assumptions need good insight - even a \"finger in the air\" guess can be based on something known. Â Each assumption also presents a risk that may need appropriate management. Â Knowing when to stop analysis should not just be a matter of time\'s up. A good complex problem solver needs to be brave and hold true to the facts using insight, teamwork and experience to judge when/how to progress.</li>\r\n 	<li><b>Creatively Solve:</b>Â  We often hear \"I can\'t see the wood for the trees\" or \"take the helicopter view\" these phrases characterise that finding new perspectives to a challenge can unlock creative solutions. Mindmaps and hierarchy models are a powerful graphical means to capture the extent of the challenge faced and break it down, systematically into smaller pieces: being free to capture elements and use techniques to group, assess inter-relationships and summarise often helps find ways to new ways to see a problem. Sometimes the solution lies around the corner - but how can we gain some insight to see around bends? Engaging all parts of the brain is key to this clue - stand up, use colours, post-its, cards and facilitated \"brainstorming\" all play their part. Â If the problem is very large and has been broken into several parts the solving may take some time. Â Teamwork, as ever, is key to good outcomes.</li>\r\n 	<li><b>RigorouslyÂ review:</b>Â So the team have creatively come up with some solution options after mapping out the problem, collecting data, suspendedÂ judgmentÂ in the analysis. But how well do the solutions meet the defined the attributes of the problem?Â  Perhaps no solutions meet the criteria - so what are the tradeoffs and who is best placed to choose? Â Complex problem solving is not necessarily a deterministic or linear process - things change. Â TheÂ underpinningÂ data and assumptions set may need regular re-evaluation to check that the selection solution path is still optimal.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div>Â Leading change in the 21st century is a survival skill and success is underpinned by finding lasting solutions to the complex problems the change presents. Sherlock Holmes is able solve some of the most complex conundrums through his methodical approach. Perhaps if some of these 5 clues are carefully examined, we too can improve our capability to solve complex problems.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<!--more-->','5 clues...   for solving complex problems','','inherit','closed','closed','','173-revision-v1','','','2017-08-14 12:50:06','2017-08-14 12:50:06','',173,'https://charlesdigital.co.uk/2017/08/14/173-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(230,1,'2017-08-14 12:59:00','2017-08-14 12:59:00','Sir Ranulph Fiennes is a remarkable character. The Guiness Book of Records says that \"Sir Ran is the greatest explorer ever\": Â he completed a transglobal navigation around the Earth, pole to pole. Â He has crossed Antartica and the Artic man-hauling 250kg sledges. Â He has run 7 marathons, in 7 continents, in 7 days. Â He has climbed Everest and the North Face of the Eiger; the only man to do this and explore both poles. Â His <a href=\"https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B00319M6UE/ref=dp-kindle-redirect?_encoding=UTF8&amp;btkr=1\">autobiography</a> is awe inspiring. When not exploring, he spends his life talking about his experiences, giving motivational speeches and raising fortunes for charity.\r\n\r\nFor us mere mortals, is there some essence from his inspiration that we can recognise in change programmes?<!--more-->\r\n\r\nPeople work in organisations for all manner of reasons: Â The classic big 3 of Money, Fulfilment and Power, tend to dominate as the most popular. Hence, it follows that carrot and stick plays well to Â Power &amp; Money: the lure of promotion with increasing influence and financial incentive, big bonus\'s etc. Â The stick of course being a reduction in these items. Â Controlling these two elements is a base human characteristic. But beyond earning enough money to life comfortably and having a good network of respectful colleagues and friends, there should be more.\r\n\r\nFulfillment is key. Â This is what makes work enjoyable, interesting, worthwhile... and stems from value, recognition, and intellectual stimulation. Recent studies on happinessÂ have shown that having clear purpose is a top driver. Â This is why many people strive for goals, like Sir Ran, that not only give personal satisfaction for the achievement but also benefit others the process. In Sir Ranulph\'s case over Â£15m of charitable fund raising. Â For teams this includes helping customers truly achieve the improvements they seek, making a difference to peoples lives or more simply just helping people do their jobs more efficiently. Â There is fulfillment is doing a job to the best of ones ability and being recognised for it.\r\n\r\nWe have seen countless examples where helping teams connect with the benefits customers receive drives fulfilment. Indeed all change programmes should carefully consider the motivation of the teams working on them, the fulfilment factors and the team engagement strategy to maximise leverage.\r\n\r\nWe don\'t all need to run ultra-marathons or survive in -80C to win out and achieve our goals, but in the dynamic of achieving excellence for end-customers, business results and teams - planning for high team fulfilment is a key success factor to include.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','There must be something better than carrot and stick?','','inherit','closed','closed','','202-revision-v1','','','2017-08-14 12:59:00','2017-08-14 12:59:00','',202,'https://charlesdigital.co.uk/2017/08/14/202-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(231,1,'2017-08-14 13:05:08','2017-08-14 13:05:08','Globalisation &amp; Digital technology is driving an ever faster pace of change. Charles Digital\'s <a href=\"https://charlesdigital.test/2017/07/03/our-focus-excellence/\">methodology</a> focuses on Excellence for End-customers, Team performance and Business outcomes. Â This is all about making sure there is a win-win-win for all parties.\n\nAlongside the rising pace of change is the rising cost of failure. Â Building on over 30 years experience Charles Digital offers expertise to help organisations:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Determine the right vision</li>\n 	<li>Establish a delivery strategy that has a realistic business case, yet is sufficiently far-sighted</li>\n 	<li>Rigorously deliver the strategy</li>\n 	<li>Monitor, control and change delivery dynamically</li>\n 	<li>Ensure that all parties achieve thier aims: benefits, financial outcomes,</li>\n</ul>','Business Change & Digital Transformation','','inherit','closed','closed','','89-autosave-v1','','','2017-08-14 13:05:08','2017-08-14 13:05:08','',89,'https://charlesdigital.co.uk/2017/08/14/89-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(232,1,'2017-08-14 13:05:24','2017-08-14 13:05:24','Globalisation &amp; Digital technology is driving an ever faster pace of change. Charles Digital\'s <a href=\"https://charlesdigital.test/2017/07/03/our-focus-excellence/\">methodology</a> focuses on Excellence for End-customers, Team performance and Business outcomes. Â This is all about making sure there is a win-win-win for all parties.\r\n\r\nAlongside the rising pace of change is the rising cost of failure. Â Building on over 30 years experience Charles Digital offers expertise to help organisations:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Determine the right vision</li>\r\n 	